Let $O$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to $\overline{AB}.$  Then $AP = 300,$ $PB = 500,$ and $OP = 1200 - PQ.$  By the Pythagorean Theorem,
\[OP^2 + OQ^2 = PQ^2.\]We want to minimize $PQ + 1200 - PQ = 1200.$  This is equivalent to minimizing $PQ^2.$  Hence, we want to minimize $OP^2 + OQ^2 = PQ^2 - 2 \cdot OP \cdot PQ.$

By the Pythagorean Theorem,
\[OQ^2 = PB^2 - OP^2 = 500^2 - (1200 - PQ)^2.\]Hence,
\[PQ^2 - 2 \cdot OP \cdot PQ + 500^2 - (1200 - PQ)^2 = PQ^2.\]This simplifies to $OP \cdot PQ = 150000.$

By the Pythagorean Theorem on right triangle $POQ,$
\[PQ^2 + OQ^2 = 1200^2.\]Hence,
\[PQ^2 + (500^2 - (1200 - PQ)^2) = 1200^2.\]This simplifies to $PQ = \boxed{805}$ meters (to the nearest meter).

The shortest distance between two points is a straight line, so the participant should run directly from $A$ to the wall, then directly from the wall to $B.$

